text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!AAVE discrimination in the Judicial system%0a%0a:Author: BrandtE%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn this article, I discuss an article about discrimination against AAVE in the judicial system.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI'm linking to an article from a Stanford linguist about discrimination in the judicial system against AAVE%0a%0ahttps://news.stanford.edu/news/2014/december/vernacular-trial-testimony-120214.html%0a%0aIn the article it takes a particularly close look at the George Zimmerman trial and the testimony from the prosecution's witness Rachel Jeantel. The article discusses how Rachel's use of AAVE (African American Vernacular English), leads her to be misunderstood and even prejudged. Situations like this one are of particular importance because of the stakes, if testimony is not understood or discredited due to a speakers use of a dialect it could mean justice isn't done or someone is wrongfully convicted. In the case of Rachel Jeantel, there are a variety of examples where Rachel uses AAVE which would be understood as ungrammatical in SAE.%0a%0aRachel uses stressed BIN: "I was been paying attention, sir". She uses preterit tense had as well as consonant metathesis in ask: "He had ask me did I go to the hospital" where ask is pronounced [æks]. She also drops copula: "He by the area where his daddy fiancée house is." where an 'is' would be included before by in SAE.%0a%0aThe article charges that because none of the jurors were African American and presumably weren't AAVE speakers, they could very well misunderstand or judge Rachel's character and by extension her testimony by the way she spoke.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210501-055118-92040#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 22:51-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-055118-92040 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Misunderstanding '''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aThe fact that the jurors may unintentionally misunderstand what Rachel is saying is a really good example of unintended inequality against those who have accents (jurors probably didn't mean to not understand you) %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-055118-92040#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
